com.yahoo.bullet.record

Class BulletRecord<T extends Serializable>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.yahoo.bullet.record.BulletRecord<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<Map.Entry<String,T>>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    TypedBulletRecord, UntypedBulletRecord

    public abstract class BulletRecord<T extends Serializable>
extends Object
implements Iterable<Map.Entry<String,T>>, Serializable
    Data sent to Bullet should be wrapped in a class that extends this abstract class. It is Serializable and Iterable so records can be used in for-each loops. The various set methods can be used to insert fields into the record. They are implemented by default to use the set(String, Object) method which should be overridden in child classes. This method delegates to the rawSet(String, Serializable) method after calling convert(Object) on it. Field names are to be provided as Strings and must be unique, otherwise the duplicate takes precedence over the first by default. Note that when using the various "set.*Map" or "set.*List" methods, the provided Map and List instances will not deep-copied and are expected to be Serializable. If not and if your particular instance of the record does not handle the conversion, a RuntimeException will be thrown. When inserting into the Record, methods are explicitly provided for each type supported (listed below). You may also use typedSet(String, TypedObject) to set a TypedObject into the record and use the various typedGet(String) methods to read data out as TypedObject When reading raw data from the Record, which may not be something needed by users of this very frequently (as it is the entry point into Bullet), you may use get(String). Casting it is left to the user. See TypedBulletRecord for an alternative. For the types supported by this record, see Type. Primitives: Type.PRIMITIVES Complex: Type.MAPS and Type.LISTS Instead of setting a field to null (you cannot for top level Java primitives), avoid setting it instead.

      • typedExtract

        public TypedObject typedExtract(String identifier)
        Extracts a field as a TypedObject from the record in a custom identifier format.
        For example, suppose a record has a map of boolean maps called "aaa". Then specifying for the identifier:
        - "aaa" will extract that map of maps
        - "aaa.bbb" will extract the inner map that "bbb" in "aaa" to (if it exists)
        - "aaa.bbb.ccc" will extract the boolean that "ccc" in "bbb" in "aaa" (if it exists)

        For list fields, replace the key in the identifier format with indices instead, e.g. "list.0" or "list.0.key". If your maps have string keys that are integers, This method will also work for extract similarly for primitive maps and lists.
        Parameters:
        identifier - The non-null identifier of the field to get.
        Returns:
        The field or TypedObject.NULL if it does not exist or the identifier does not match the type.

      • toUnmodifiableDataMap

        public Map<String,Serializable> toUnmodifiableDataMap()
        Creates a read-only copy of the raw data in the record as a Map with keys being the names of the fields and values being the raw data stored in the record. The raw data stored need not be necessarily of the generic type of record. Note, this does not prevent you from accessing the underlying values and modifying them and if you do, the record makes no guarantees on correctness of calls thereafter.
        Returns:
        A Collections.unmodifiableMap(Map) of the raw data in the record.
